{"parse":{"title":"Berry Plan","pageid":56778142,"revid":838517978,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Berry Plan</b> was a <a href=\"/wiki/Vietnam_War\" title=\"Vietnam War\">Vietnam War</a>-era program in the United States that allowed physicians to defer <a href=\"/wiki/Conscription_in_the_United_States\" title=\"Conscription in the United States\">obligatory military service</a> until they had completed <a href=\"/wiki/Medical_school\" title=\"Medical school\">medical school</a> and residency training.<sup id=\"cite_ref-clark_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-clark-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> More than 42,000 physicians and surgeons were affected by the Berry Plan, named after Dr. Frank B. Berry, who served as the <a href=\"/wiki/Assistant_Secretary_of_Defense_for_Health_Affairs\" title=\"Assistant Secretary of Defense for Health Affairs\">Assistant Secretary of Defense for Health and Medical Affairs</a> from 1954\u20131961.<sup id=\"cite_ref-clark_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-clark-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The Plan, enacted in 1954, arose out of a proposed \"Doctor's Draft,\" originally met with objections from the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Medical_Association\" title=\"American Medical Association\">American Medical Association</a>, The <a href=\"/wiki/Association_of_American_Medical_Colleges\" title=\"Association of American Medical Colleges\">Association of American Medical Colleges</a>, and the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Hospital_Association\" title=\"American Hospital Association\">American Hospital Association</a>, who felt the draft would deprive them of a pool of young men who would staff their hospitals. The Berry Plan offered draftees three choices: entry into the Armed Forces after completing a <a href=\"/wiki/Medical_internship#United_States\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Medical internship\">medical internship</a>, after completing one year of <a href=\"/wiki/Residency_(medicine)#United_States\" title=\"Residency (medicine)\">residency</a> and returning to their residencies after completion of service, and after completion of a full residency program. The Berry Plan ended in 1973, with the last four physicians to complete their education and training entering the armed forces in 1980.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Berry_Plan&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Conscription_in_the_United_States\" title=\"Conscription in the United States\">Conscription in the United States</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Selective_Service_System\" title=\"Selective Service System\">Selective Service System</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Berry_Plan&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-clark-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-clark_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-clark_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Alfred E. Clark (October 16, 1976). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1976/10/16/archives/frank-b-berry-chief-of-defense-doctors-surgeon-84-devised-program.html\">\"Frank B. Berry, Chief of Defense Doctors\"</a>. <i>The New York Times</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 March</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=Frank+B.+Berry%2C+Chief+of+Defense+Doctors&amp;rft.date=1976-10-16&amp;rft.au=Alfred+E.+Clark&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F1976%2F10%2F16%2Farchives%2Ffrank-b-berry-chief-of-defense-doctors-surgeon-84-devised-program.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABerry+Plan\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Berry FB (1976). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1808239\">\"The story of \"the Berry Plan<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a>. <i>Bull N Y Acad Med</i>. <b>52</b> (3): 278\u201382. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Central\" title=\"PubMed Central\">PMC</a>&#160;<span class=\"plainlinks\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1808239\">1808239</a>&#8239;<img alt=\"Freely accessible\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/9px-Lock-green.svg.png\" title=\"Freely accessible\" width=\"9\" height=\"14\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/14px-Lock-green.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Lock-green.svg/18px-Lock-green.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"813\" /></span>. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/766868\">766868</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39